# Toronto Rising — author session facts (ask, don't speculate)

The author is available in chat. When diagnosis depends on **their** runtime or workflow, **ask** — do not guess and present guesses as likely causes.

## Do not speculate in chat or docs

Avoid phrasing like:

- "You may not have Save & Play'd yet"
- "Perhaps you clicked the bag manually"
- "The GUID in the save might still be the old one"
- "This might only happen if you skipped step N"

State what **code and logs prove**, then ask a **direct confirmation question** when the next step depends on author-only facts.

## Ask instead (examples)

| Unknown | Ask |
| --- | --- |
| Bundled Lua vs repo | "Did you Save & Play after the last build?" |
| Repro path | "Was that die from the E2E spawn helper or a manual bag click?" |
| Live object identity | "Is `2cb469` still the Brown hunger bag GUID in your current save?" |
| Test harness state | "Did you re-arm `RunTest('Dice', 'F')` after the failure, or continue the same step?" |
| In-game observation | "What did you see on the table when F1 failed — bag Y, staged dice count, console lines?" |

One or two targeted questions beat a paragraph of alternate theories.

## When asking is required

- Root-cause analysis where **two or more** explanations are equally plausible from code alone
- Closing a bugfix or E2E pass as "fixed" when verification is in-game
- Blaming stale bundle, wrong GUID, manual vs automated path, or load-order without evidence

## When asking is optional

- Code review of a PR diff with no runtime claim
- Explaining documented behavior that does not depend on the author's session
- The author already stated the fact in the same thread (do not re-ask)

